My lover’s got humor
She’s the giggle at a funeral
Knows everybody’s disapproval
I should’ve worshipped her sooner
output_1: The lyrics describe a person who is in love with someone who has a unique sense of humor. The person is described as being able to find humor in even the most somber of situations, such as a funeral. Despite the disapproval of others, the person in love with this person continues to admire and appreciate them. The metaphors in this lyrics suggest that the person in love is someone who is able to find joy and happiness in the face of adversity, and that they are someone who is not easily swayed by the opinions of others.
output_2:
This set of lyrics describes the power of humor and laughter in the face of adversity. The metaphors used in the lyrics are:

1. "She’s the giggle at a funeral" - This metaphor suggests that the person in question has a way of finding humor in difficult or sad situations, much like a giggle at a funeral. This person is able to bring joy and levity to even the most somber of settings.
2. "Knows everybody’s disapproval" - This suggests that the person is aware of the disapproval of others, but doesn't let it affect her. She is confident in her own sense of humor and doesn't let the opinions of others bring her down.
3. "I should’ve worshipped her sooner" - This line implies that the speaker wishes they had recognized the significance of the person's humor and wit earlier in life. The metaphorical nature of the phrase suggests that the speaker believes the person is a rare and valuable find.

instruction: Suggest some Audiobooks for First-Time Listeners. You can attract them by choosing popular works.
output_1:
Sure, here are some popular audiobooks that are great for first-time listeners:

1. "The Alchemist" by Paulo Coelho - This is a classic novel about a young shepherd who sets out on a journey to fulfill his personal legend. It's a great introduction to audiobooks because it's an easy listen and has a great narrator.
2. "The 7 Habits of Highly Effective People" by Stephen Covey - This is a self-help book that has been a bestseller for decades. It's a great listen for anyone looking to improve their personal or professional life.
3. "The Girl on the Train" by Paula Hawkins - This is a thrilling mystery novel that follows the story of a woman who becomes entangled in a missing persons case. It's a great listen for anyone who loves a good suspense story.
4. "The Kite Runner" by Khaled Hosseini - This is a heart-wrenching novel about the friendship between two boys growing up in Afghanistan. It's a great listen for anyone who loves a good story about friendship and redemption.
5. "The Subtle Art of Not Giving a F\*ck" by Mark Manson - This is a self-help book that encourages readers to focus on the things that truly matter in life. It's a great listen for anyone who wants to learn how to prioritize their time and energy.
6. "The 4-Hour Work Week" by Timothy Ferriss - This is a self-help book that encourages readers to live a more fulfilling life by automating their income and outsourcing their work. It's a great listen for anyone who wants to learn how to work less and live more.
7. "The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy" by Douglas Adams - This is a humorous science fiction novel that follows the story of an alien and his human friend as they travel through space. It's a great listen for anyone who loves a good laugh and a good science fiction story.

These are just a few of the many great audiobooks available for first-time listeners. I hope you find something that interests you!

instruction:
You should take the time to read the situation and problem carefully and give the best advice you can.

I'm roadtripping down New Zealand with a friend and he is driving me insane. He hasn't enjoyed all the tours we've been on and doesn't want to chat about ANYTHING. We're a week into our trip and this is the quietest I've ever been when hanging out with another person as he rebuffs all my attempts at conversation. He wears his airpods in the car and around the accommodation - not that I've kept trying to talk to him. Honestly, he is bringing some seriously bad vibes to everything and it's ruining my trip.
We don't have anything booked in yet for the South Island, so I'm planning to ditch him in Wellington at the ferry. Probably book my own car in Picton and just relax alone for the rest of the trip. (Just thinking about it is such sharp relief that it makes me feel emotional. I'll pay whatever price I have to just to get away from him.)
Obviously telling him he is ruining my trip with his negative energy isn't the best way to approach this.
Any advice for the best approach so we can split amicably? Or at least not have an argument that ends with very hurt feelings?
output_1:
It sounds like you're feeling really frustrated and unhappy with the situation, and I'm sorry to hear that. It's understandable that you want to enjoy your trip and have a positive experience with your friend, but it's also important to prioritize your own well-being and happiness.

Before you have a conversation with your friend, it might be helpful to take some time to reflect on your own feelings and needs. What do you want to get out of this trip? What are your priorities? What are your boundaries? It can be helpful to have a clear understanding of these things before you approach the conversation with your friend.

When you do have the conversation with your friend, it's important to approach it in a calm and respectful way. You might try saying something like, "I've been feeling really frustrated and unhappy with the way things have been going on this trip. I want to make sure we can both enjoy ourselves and have a positive experience, but I also need to prioritize my own well-being and happiness. I'm not sure if this is something we can work through, but I wanted to talk to you about it and see if we can find a way to make this trip work for both of us."

It's important to listen to your friend's perspective and try to understand their feelings and needs as well. It's possible that there are underlying issues or concerns that are contributing to their behavior, and it might be helpful to explore those together.

If, after the conversation, you decide that it's not possible to continue the trip together in a way that works for both of you, it's important to do so in a respectful and amicable way. You might try saying something like, "I appreciate the time we've spent together on this trip, but I think it's best if we go our separate ways. I wish you all the best and hope that we can remain friends in the future."

Remember that it's okay to prioritize your own well-being and happiness, and it's okay to make changes or adjustments to your plans if it means that you'll have a better experience.
output_2:
I understand your frustration, but it's important to approach this situation with sensitivity and respect. Here's a possible way to address the situation:

1. Schedule a conversation: Find a time when you both are calm and have some privacy. Let your friend know that you value their company, but you've noticed that you're not enjoying the trip as much as you'd hoped because of the lack of conversation.
2. Be specific: Share some examples of situations where you felt uncomfortable or unhappy because of the lack of interaction. Avoid blaming or accusing your friend, and focus on how you're feeling.
3. Suggest solutions: Propose some activities or approaches to conversation that you think might help improve the dynamic between you. For instance, you could suggest taking turns choosing a topic of conversation or finding common interests to discuss.
4. Be open to compromise: If your friend is willing to try some of these suggestions, be open to compromise and give it a chance. Remember that change takes time, and it's important to be patient and understanding.
5. End on a positive note: Express your gratitude for the trip so far and emphasize that you hope you can continue to enjoy the journey together.

Remember, the goal here is to have an honest and respectful conversation that can help you both understand each other's needs and preferences. By approaching the situation with empathy and understanding, you can increase the chances of finding a solution that works for both of you.

instruction:
A job description is a document that clearly states the requirements, duties, responsibilities, and skills required to perform a specific role. You need to write a job description based on the given information. You should describe responsibilities and duties in your job description in a logical order. Remember that potential employees often get their first impression of your company from your job description. So, the job description should convey the attractiveness of your company.

Company: [Company name]
Job: Software Engineer
Job Responsibilities:
Receive and perform code reviews with other engineers.
Write unit, integration, and end-to-end tests to verify functionality using automated testing frameworks such as Pytest.
Work collaboratively with fellow software engineers to build features requested by business stakeholders.
Participate in Agile teams to develop, test, and debug complex data processing pipelines and data analysis applications using big data processing systems such as Apache Spark.
Diagnose, debug, and perform root cause analysis of issues and defects.
Skills and experience that will lead to success:
Experience with a modern software programming language. We use Python, and Pyspark extensively.
Experience with cloud systems like AWS or Azure
Experience writing SQL queries 
Strong written and verbal communication skills
Eagerness to work in a highly-collaborative environment
Some visualization experience such as Tableau or PowerBI is helpful
output_1:
Job Title: Software Engineer

Job Summary:
We are seeking a highly skilled and motivated Software Engineer to join our team. The successful candidate will be responsible for collaborating with other engineers to build features requested by business stakeholders, participating in Agile teams to develop, test, and debug complex data processing pipelines and data analysis applications using big data processing systems such as Apache Spark. The ideal candidate will have experience with modern software programming languages, cloud systems, and SQL queries, as well as strong written and verbal communication skills.

Job Responsibilities:

* Collaborate with other engineers to receive and perform code reviews
* Write unit, integration, and end-to-end tests to verify functionality using automated testing frameworks such as Pytest
* Participate in Agile teams to develop, test, and debug complex data processing pipelines and data analysis applications using big data processing systems such as Apache Spark
* Diagnose, debug, and perform root cause analysis of issues and defects
* Participate in code reviews and provide constructive feedback to improve the quality of the codebase
* Collaborate with other teams to ensure that software solutions meet business requirements
* Stay up-to-date with the latest trends and best practices in software engineering

Skills and Experience:

* Strong experience with a modern software programming language, preferably Python and Pyspark
* Experience with cloud systems such as AWS or Azure
* Experience writing SQL queries
* Strong written and verbal communication skills
* Eagerness to work in a highly-collaborative environment
* Some visualization experience such as Tableau or PowerBI is helpful
* Bachelor's degree in Computer Science or related field

We offer a competitive salary and benefits package, as well as opportunities for professional growth and development. If you are passionate about software engineering and want to work in a dynamic and collaborative environment, we encourage you to apply for this exciting opportunity.
output_2:
Job Title: Software Engineer

Job Summary:
We are seeking a Software Engineer to join our team of talented professionals. The ideal candidate will be responsible for writing unit, integration, and end-to-end tests, collaborating with other engineers, and participating in Agile teams to develop and debug complex data processing pipelines and data analysis applications.

Job Duties:

1. Collaborate with other engineers to receive and perform code reviews.
2. Write unit, integration, and end-to-end tests to verify functionality using automated testing frameworks such as Pytest.
3. Participate in Agile teams to develop, test, and debug complex data processing pipelines and data analysis applications using big data processing systems such as Apache Spark.
4. Diagnose, debug, and perform root cause analysis of issues and defects.

Requirements:

1. Experience with modern software programming languages such as Python and Pyspark.
2. Experience with cloud systems such as AWS or Azure.
3. Proficiency in writing SQL queries.
4. Strong written and verbal communication skills.
5. Eagerness to work in a highly-collaborative environment.
6. Some visualization experience using tools such as Tableau or PowerBI is helpful.

We offer a dynamic and challenging work environment, opportunities for professional growth, and a competitive salary package. If you are passionate about software engineering and eager to work in a collaborative environment, we encourage you to apply for this exciting opportunity.

instruction:
Write a section for a blog post and try to cover all of the provided information about this section in your text.

Blog Topic: 7 Fall Fashion Trends Worth Taking on Your Trip
Section Title: Trusty Jeans
Main point of the section: jeans can be worn all year and look good with everything .
output_1:
When it comes to fashion, it's important to have pieces that can transition seamlessly from season to season. One such piece that is always a reliable and versatile option is a pair of trusty jeans. Whether you're hitting the town or exploring a new city, a good pair of jeans can be dressed up or down to fit the occasion.

This fall, jeans are still a staple in many people's wardrobes. They come in a variety of washes, fits, and styles, so there's something for everyone. Darker washes and more relaxed fits are popular this season, but don't be afraid to mix it up with a lighter wash or a more tailored fit.

One of the great things about jeans is that they can be worn with just about anything. A simple t-shirt and sneakers is a classic look, but you can also dress them up with a blazer or heels for a more polished look. Jeans also look great with boots, booties, or sneakers, so they're a great option for a casual weekend getaway or a more formal trip.

In addition to being versatile, jeans are also comfortable and durable. They're a great option for travel because they're easy to pack and can withstand being stuffed in a bag for long periods of time. Plus, they're a great option for exploring a new city because they're easy to move around in.

Overall, jeans are a great option for anyone looking for a reliable and versatile piece to add to their fall wardrobe. They're comfortable, durable, and can be dressed up or down to fit any occasion. So, next time you're packing for a trip, consider adding a pair of trusty jeans to your suitcase.
output_2:
Trusty Jeans: A Staple for Any Season

Jeans are a timeless piece of clothing that can be worn all year round. They are a staple in anyone's wardrobe, and are versatile enough to be dressed up or down. This makes them the perfect addition to any travel wardrobe.

One of the reasons jeans are so popular is that they are easy to style. They can be paired with a simple t-shirt and sneakers for a casual look, or with a blazer and heels for a more formal occasion. They also look great with a variety of tops and jackets, making them a great option for layering.

Another benefit of jeans is their durability. They are made to withstand wear and tear, making them perfect for travel where you may need to move around a lot or sit on the ground. They also provide comfort and support, making them a great option for long flights or road trips.

In the fall, jeans can be dressed up with a sweater or a scarf for a cozy and chic look. They also look great with boots, making them a great option for a fall trip. Whether you're heading to a cold climate or a warm one, jeans are a great option for any season.

In conclusion, jeans are a versatile and durable piece of clothing that can be worn all year round. They are a great addition to any travel wardrobe, and are perfect for any occasion.

Discuss the origins and history of the word that has been given to you.

oblique

The word "oblique" comes from the Latin word "obliquus," which means "sloping" or "askew." The word entered the English language in the 14th century, and has since been used to describe a variety of things that are slanted or at an angle.

In its most basic sense, "oblique" refers to something that is not straight or perpendicular. This can apply to physical objects, such as a building with an oblique angle, or to abstract concepts, such as an oblique approach to a problem.

In art and design, "oblique" is often used to describe a diagonal line or shape. In music, an oblique interval is one that is not a perfect fifth or octave. In literature, an oblique reference is a subtle or indirect allusion to something.

Overall, the word "oblique" has been used in a variety of contexts throughout history, reflecting its versatility and the many different ways in which it can be applied.
output_2:
The word "oblique" comes from the Latin word "obliquus," which means "not straight, inclined, or slanting." The Latin word is derived from "ob-," which means "against" and "liquus," meaning "free." The term "oblique" has been used in various languages, including French, Spanish, and English, since the 14th century.

In the English language, the word "oblique" has been used in many contexts, such as in geometry to describe angles that are not perpendicular to the line of sight, in art to refer to a diagonal line or shape, and in literature to describe a character who is not straightforward or honest. It has also been used in politics to describe someone who is not straightforward or honest.

The word "oblique" has been a part of the English language for several centuries, and its usage has evolved over time to reflect the changing meanings and connotations of the term.

instruction: Write a step-by-step guide for resolving GitHub merge conflicts.
output_1:
GitHub merge conflicts can be a frustrating experience, but with the right approach, they can be resolved quickly and easily. Here is a step-by-step guide for resolving GitHub merge conflicts:

1. Identify the conflict: The first step is to identify the conflict. This can be done by opening the file in question and looking for lines with a "<<<<<<<", "=======", and ">>>>>>>" notation. These notations indicate that there is a conflict in that section of the file.

2. Open a pull request: Once you have identified the conflict, open a pull request to merge the changes into your repository. This will allow you to see the changes that are causing the conflict.

3. Review the changes: Carefully review the changes that are causing the conflict. Look for any lines that are different between the two branches and try to determine which changes should be kept and which should be discarded.

4. Resolve the conflict: Once you have determined which changes should be kept and which should be discarded, you can resolve the conflict. This can be done by editing the file and removing the conflict markers.

5. Commit the changes: After resolving the conflict, commit the changes to your branch. Make sure to include a meaningful commit message that describes the changes you made.

6. Push the changes: Once you have committed the changes, push them to your branch. This will update your local repository with the changes.

7. Merge the branch: Finally, you can merge the branch into your repository. This will apply the changes to your repository and resolve the conflict.

By following these steps, you can easily resolve GitHub merge conflicts and keep your repository up-to-date.
output_2:
Step 1: Identify the Conflict

The first step in resolving a merge conflict is to identify the conflict itself. This can be done by opening the conflicting file in a text editor, or by using the GitHub Desktop client to mark the conflicts.

Step 2: Review the Conflicting Changes

Once you have identified the conflict, review the changes that caused the conflict. Look at the changes made by both branches, and try to understand why they are conflicting.

Step 3: Choose a Resolution

Next, choose a resolution for the conflict. This may involve deciding which changes to keep, which to discard, or which to modify. You may also need to consider the impact of your resolution on other parts of the codebase.

Step 4: Apply the Resolution

Once you have chosen a resolution, apply it to the conflict. This can be done by using a text editor to make the necessary changes, or by using the GitHub Desktop client to apply the changes.

Step 5: Verify the Resolution

After applying the resolution, verify that the conflict has been resolved. You can do this by opening the conflicting file in a text editor, or by using the GitHub Desktop client to verify that the conflict has been resolved.

Step 6: Commit the Resolution

Finally, commit the resolution to the repository. This can be done using the GitHub Desktop client, or by using the command line interface. Be sure to include a detailed commit message that describes the changes made to resolve the conflict.

instruction:
One or more jobs can be run automatically by a workflow. The workflows are defined in the repository as YAML files and will run if an event occurs in the repository, as well as manually, or on a certain schedule.
Bring an example of a workflow that demonstrate the CI/CD features of GitHub Actions.
output_1:
Sure, here's an example of a GitHub Actions workflow that demonstrates CI/CD features:
```yaml
name: CI/CD workflow

on:
  push:
    branches:
      - main
  pull_request:
    branches:
      - main

jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
    - name: Checkout code
      uses: actions/checkout@v2
    - name: Set up Node.js
      uses: actions/setup-node@v2
      with:
        node-version: 14.x
    - name: Run tests
      run: |
        npm install
        npm test
    - name: Build package
      run: |
        npm run build
    - name: Publish package
      uses: peaceiris/actions-gh-pages@v3
      with:
        github_token: ${{ secrets.GITHUB_TOKEN }}
        publish_dir: ./dist
```
In this workflow, the `build` job runs on the `main` branch when a push event occurs or when a pull request is opened against the `main` branch. The job checks out the code, sets up Node.js, runs tests, builds the package, and publishes it to the GitHub Pages.

The `on` section specifies the events that trigger the workflow. In this example, the workflow runs on push events to the `main` branch and pull request events to the `main` branch.

The `jobs` section defines the jobs that run in the workflow. The `build` job is the only job defined in this example.

The `steps` section defines the steps that run in the job. The `Checkout code` step checks out the code from the repository. The `Set up Node.js` step installs Node.js and sets the version to 14.x. The `Run tests` step runs the tests using `npm test`. The `Build package` step runs `npm run build` to build the package. The `Publish package` step uses the `peaceiris/actions-gh-pages` action to publish the package to GitHub Pages.

This workflow demonstrates how GitHub Actions can be used for continuous integration and continuous deployment by automatically building and publishing the package to GitHub Pages whenever changes are pushed to the `main` branch.
output_2:
Here is an example of a GitHub Actions workflow that demonstrates the CI/CD features:
```bash
name: CI/CD

on:
  push:
    branches:
      - main

jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
    - name: Checkout code
      uses: actions/checkout@v2
    - name: Build
      run: |
        npm ci
        npm run build
    - name: Test
      run: |
        npm run test
```
This workflow is triggered on pushes to the `main` branch and runs on an Ubuntu machine. It consists of three steps:

1. Checkout the code
2. Build the project using `npm ci` and `npm run build`
3. Run the tests using `npm run test`

This workflow demonstrates the CI/CD features of GitHub Actions by automatically building and testing the code when changes are pushed to the main branch.

instruction:
Write a short analysis of the cinematography in the movie.

Dead Poets Society
output_1:
Dead Poets Society is a 1989 American drama film directed by Peter Weir and starring Robin Williams. The cinematography in the movie is a significant aspect of its overall aesthetic and narrative. The film is set in a prestigious boys' prep school in the 1950s, and the cinematography captures the period's aesthetic, with its focus on order, discipline, and conformity. The camera work is often static, with long takes and a focus on the characters' faces, emphasizing their emotions and inner thoughts.

The film's cinematography also highlights the contrast between the school's rigid structure and the characters' desire for individuality and self-expression. The use of lighting and color is also significant, with the school's interiors often being dimly lit and the exteriors featuring muted colors, reflecting the film's themes of conformity and repression.

The film's most iconic scene, the "carpe diem" sequence, is a masterful example of the cinematography's ability to convey the characters' emotions and the film's themes. The scene features the boys standing on their desks, reciting a poem, and the camera work captures the sense of exhilaration and rebellion that the scene represents.

Overall, the cinematography in Dead Poets Society is a crucial element of the film's aesthetic and narrative, capturing the period's aesthetic, highlighting the contrast between conformity and individuality, and conveying the characters' emotions and themes.
output_2:
The cinematography in Dead Poets Society is a key component in creating the overall atmosphere and mood of the film. The film is set primarily in the prestigious Welton Academy, an all-boys prep school, and the cinematography is used to convey the claustrophobic and oppressive atmosphere of the institution. The tight close-ups on the actors' faces and the low-angle shots that emphasize the characters' power dynamics within the school serve to create a sense of confinement and control.

However, the film also employs more dynamic shots, such as the use of widescreen shots during the poetry recitations, to convey the characters' passion and the emotional release they find through their poetry. The use of natural lighting, particularly during the outdoor scenes, also adds to the film's emotional impact, bringing the beauty of nature into the story. Overall, the cinematography in Dead Poets Society is a vital element in conveying the themes of the film and creating a rich visual experience for the audience.

instruction:
Answer the following question.

How do I compare strings in Java?
I've been using the == operator in my program to compare all my strings so far. However, I ran into a bug, changed one of them into .equals() instead, and it fixed the bug.
Is == bad? When should it and should it not be used? What's the difference?
output_1:
The == operator compares the memory addresses of two objects, not their values. This means that if two objects have the same value, but different memory addresses, they will be considered different by the == operator.

The .equals() method, on the other hand, compares the values of two objects. This means that if two objects have the same value, they will be considered equal by the .equals() method, regardless of their memory addresses.

In general, it is recommended to use the .equals() method to compare strings in Java, rather than the == operator. The == operator can be misleading and can lead to bugs in your code.

It is also important to note that the .equals() method is not the same as the == operator for objects of type String. The .equals() method for String objects compares the characters of the strings, not the memory addresses.

In summary, the == operator should not be used to compare strings in Java, as it compares the memory addresses of two objects, not their values. Instead, use the .equals() method to compare the values of two strings.
output_2:
The "==" operator is generally not recommended for comparing strings in Java. It is used for comparing primitive values and objects based on their memory location, which can lead to unexpected results.

The correct way to compare strings in Java is to use the .equals() method. This method compares the content of the strings, not just their memory locations.

So, in your case, the change from == to .equals() fixed the bug because it compared the content of the strings correctly.

In general, the "==" operator should be used for primitive types and objects of the same class, but for different classes, you should use .equals() method for comparison.

instruction:

Table: Person
| Column Name | Type     |

| lastName         | varchar |
| firstName         | varchar |
personId is the primary key column for this table.
This table contains information about the ID of some persons and their first and last names.
Table: Address
| Column Name | Type     |
| addressId        | int         |
| personId          | int         |
| city                   | varchar|
| state                | varchar |
addressId is the primary key column for this table.

Write an SQL query to report the first name, last name, city, and state of each person in the Person table. If the address of a personId is not present in the Address table, report null instead.
Return the result table in any order.
Implementation:
select FirstName, LastName, City, State
from Person left join Address
on Person.PersonId = Address.PersonId
;

The query selects the FirstName, LastName, City, and State columns from the Person and Address tables. The result of the query will be a table that contains the first name, last name, city, and state of each person in the Person table, along with null values for any rows where there is no matching address in the Address table.

The query returns the result table in any order, which means that the order of the rows in the result table is not guaranteed. If you want to specify a particular order for the rows, you can use an ORDER BY clause in the query.

Overall, the implementation is a simple and effective way to solve the given problem. It uses a left join to combine the Person and Address tables, and selects the relevant columns to get the desired information. The result is a table that contains the first name, last name, city, and state of each person in the Person table, along with null values for any missing addresses.

Mathematics and art have a long historical relationship. Persistent popular claims have been made for the use of the golden ratio in ancient art and architecture, without reliable evidence. In the Italian Renaissance, Luca Pacioli wrote the influential treatise De divina proportione (1509), illustrated with woodcuts by Leonardo da Vinci, on the use of the golden ratio in art. Another Italian painter, Piero della Francesca, developed Euclid's ideas on perspective in treatises such as De Prospectiva Pingendi, and in his paintings. The engraver Albrecht Dürer made many references to mathematics in his work Melencolia I. In modern times, the graphic artist M. C. Escher made intensive use of tessellation and hyperbolic geometry, with the help of the mathematician H. S. M. Coxeter, while the De Stijl movement led by Theo van Doesburg and Piet Mondrian explicitly embraced geometrical forms. Mathematics has inspired textile arts such as quilting, knitting, cross-stitch, crochet, embroidery, weaving, Turkish and other carpet-making, as well as kilim. In Islamic art, symmetries are evident in forms as varied as Persian girih and Moroccan zellige tilework, Mughal jali pierced stone screens, and widespread muqarnas vaulting.

Conventional trade practices often prioritize the interests of multinational corporations and result in the exploitation of workers, environmental degradation, and the destruction of local communities.

It also promotes the use of environmentally sustainable practices, such as the use of renewable resources and the reduction of waste. This view is based on the belief that trade should be a means of promoting human well-being and development, rather than a tool for exploitation and oppression.

instruction: Give students tips on how to keep their nerves under control during class presentations.
output_1:
Here are some tips to help students keep their nerves under control during class presentations:

1. Practice, practice, practice: The more you practice your presentation, the more comfortable you will feel when it's time to deliver it. Rehearse in front of a mirror, with a friend or family member, or even by yourself until you feel confident.

2. Use positive self-talk: Instead of focusing on the negative thoughts that may be causing your nerves, try to reframe them in a positive way. For example, instead of thinking "I'm going to mess this up," tell yourself "I'm going to do my best and it's okay if I make a mistake."

3. Take deep breaths: When you start to feel nervous, take a few deep breaths to help calm your nerves. Inhale deeply through your nose and exhale slowly through your mouth.

4. Focus on your audience: Instead of focusing on your own nerves, try to focus on your audience. Connect with them and try to make a connection with them. This will help you feel more comfortable and confident.

5. Use visualization techniques: Visualize yourself delivering a successful presentation. Imagine yourself speaking confidently and clearly, and receiving positive feedback from your audience.

6. Remember that it's okay to make mistakes: Nobody is perfect, and it's okay to make mistakes during a presentation. If you do make a mistake, don't let it throw you off. Simply correct it and move on.

7. Take care of yourself: Make sure you are well-rested, well-fed, and hydrated before your presentation. This will help you feel more energized and focused.

By following these tips, you can help keep your nerves under control during class presentations and deliver a successful presentation.
output_2:
1. Practice: The more you practice, the more confident you will feel when it's time to present. Rehearse your presentation in front of friends or family to get a feel for how you will appear on stage.

2. Stay calm: Take deep breaths and try to relax before the presentation. Try not to let your nerves get the best of you.

3. Use positive affirmations: Repeat positive affirmations to yourself, such as "I am confident and capable," to help keep your nerves under control.

4. Use visualization: Visualize yourself delivering a successful presentation, envisioning positive reactions from your audience.

5. Focus on the content: Instead of worrying about your nerves, focus on the content of your presentation. Know your material inside and out, and try to stay focused on the topic.

6. Get support: If you're feeling overwhelmed, don't be afraid to reach out to friends or family members for support. They can offer words of encouragement and help you stay focused.

7. Take breaks: If you're feeling nervous, take a moment to take a deep breath and step away from the presentation. This can help you feel more calm and focused when you return.

instruction:
Provide a detailed explanation of the steps that are required in order to construct the given project.

Steam Engine Using an Empty Beer Can
output_1:
Constructing a steam engine using an empty beer can is a fun and educational project that can be done with basic materials. Here are the steps to follow:

1. Gather materials: You will need an empty beer can, a cork, a rubber band, a piece of copper wire, a nail, a piece of cloth, and some water.

2. Prepare the beer can: Cut off the top of the beer can using a can opener. Make sure to leave enough of the can intact so that it can be reused.

3. Create a seal: Place the cork in the opening of the beer can and wrap the rubber band around it to create a seal.

4. Create a valve: Cut a small hole in the cloth and place it over the cork. The hole should be small enough to allow steam to escape but large enough to allow air to enter.

5. Create a steam chamber: Cut a small hole in the side of the beer can and insert the copper wire. This will create a steam chamber that will allow steam to build up and push the piston.

6. Attach the piston: Place the nail in the center of the cloth and attach it to the copper wire. This will act as the piston.

7. Fill the can with water: Fill the beer can with water until it is about half full.

8. Light the fire: Light a small fire using a match or lighter.

9. Heat the can: Place the beer can over the fire until it starts to steam.

10. Observe the piston: As the steam builds up in the can, it will push the piston, causing it to move back and forth.

11. Experiment with different sizes and shapes of cans: You can experiment with different sizes and shapes of cans to see how they affect the performance of the steam engine.

12. Clean up: Once you are finished, make sure to dispose of the materials properly and clean up any mess.

This project is a great way to learn about the principles of steam power and how they can be used to create movement. It is also a fun and creative way to recycle an empty beer can.

As the heat source burns, the water in the cork will heat up and turn into steam. The steam will push against the rubber band, causing it to compress and create a seal. This will prevent the steam from escaping the can.

Step 10: Cool down
Once the heat source is extinguished, the steam engine will stop working. Allow the steam to dissipate, and then open the can to release the pressure.

instruction: Develop a mental exercise that can help people manage their anxiety and explain how it works.
output_1:
One mental exercise that can help people manage their anxiety is called "grounding." Grounding is a technique that helps individuals focus on the present moment and calm their racing thoughts. Here's how it works:

1. Start by finding a comfortable position, either sitting or standing.
2. Take a deep breath in and out, and focus on your breath as you inhale and exhale.
3. Begin to notice your surroundings, paying attention to the sights, sounds, and smells around you.
4. Identify five things you can see, four things you can hear, three things you can feel, two things you can taste, and one thing you can smell.
5. Once you've identified these five sensory experiences, try to engage with them fully. For example, if you see a tree, try to notice the texture of its leaves, the color of its bark, and the shape of its branches.
6. As you engage with your surroundings, try to let go of any thoughts or worries that come up. Instead, focus on the present moment and the sensory experiences around you.
7. Continue this exercise for a few minutes, until you feel more calm and centered.

Grounding works by helping individuals shift their focus from their racing thoughts and worries to the present moment. By engaging with their senses and paying attention to their surroundings, individuals can calm their minds and reduce their anxiety levels. Additionally, grounding can help individuals become more mindful and aware of their thoughts and emotions, which can lead to greater self-awareness and emotional regulation.
output_2:
One mental exercise that can help people manage their anxiety is called "the 5-4-3-2-1 technique." This exercise helps to ground the person in the present moment and brings their focus away from their anxiety. Here's how it works:

1. Start by taking a deep breath in and out. This helps to calm the body and mind.
2. Then, look around you and find five things that you can see. These can be objects or people.
3. Next, focus on four things that you can hear, such as the sound of a bird chirping or the noise of the wind.
4. Then, identify three things that you can touch, such as a soft blanket or a cool breeze.
5. Finally, bring your attention to two things that you can smell, like the scent of coffee or fresh flowers.
6. Lastly, bring your attention to one thing that you are grateful for, such as a good friend or a supportive family member.

By focusing on these five senses and the present moment, this exercise helps to distract the person from their anxious thoughts and bring them back to the present. It also helps to create a sense of calm and control, which can reduce anxiety levels.

instruction: Give a grammar tip on how to end a German verb.
output_1:
In German, verbs can be inflected to indicate the tense, mood, and person of the subject. To end a German verb, you need to add the appropriate ending based on the tense and person of the subject. Here are some general rules:

- For the present tense, add the ending "-e" for the first person singular (I) and "-en" for all other persons. For example, "ich lache" (I laugh) and "wir lachen" (we laugh).
- For the past tense, add the ending "-te" for the first person singular (I) and "-ten" for all other persons. For example, "ich lachte" (I laughed) and "wir lachten" (we laughed).
- For the future tense, add the ending "-e" for the first person singular (I) and "-en" for all other persons. For example, "ich lache" (I will laugh) and "wir lachen" (we will laugh).
- For the perfect tense, add the ending "-t" for the first person singular (I) and "-t" for all other persons. For example, "ich habe gelacht" (I have laughed) and "wir haben gelacht" (we have laughed).

It's important to note that there are many irregular verbs in German that do not follow these rules. Therefore, it's important to learn the specific endings for each verb.
output_2: The endings of German verbs can vary depending on the tense, person, and number. In the present tense, the verb usually ends with -e when it is the third person singular. For example, "Ich laufe" (I run) and "er läuft" (he runs). In the past tense, the verb usually ends with -te when it is the third person singular. For example, "Ich lief" (I ran) and "er lief" (he ran).

instruction:
Describe how to prepare the given food in your own words. Note down the ingredients you will need and the steps you will take to prepare them.

Chewy Chocolate Chip Cookies
output_1:
To prepare chewy chocolate chip cookies, you will need the following ingredients:

Ingredients:
- 2 1/4 cups all-purpose flour
- 1 tsp baking soda
- 1 tsp salt
- 1 cup unsalted butter, softened
- 1/2 cup white sugar
- 1/2 cup brown sugar
- 1 tsp vanilla extract
- 2 large eggs
- 2 cups semisweet chocolate chips

Steps:

1. Preheat your oven to 375°F (190°C). Line a baking sheet with parchment paper.

2. In a medium bowl, whisk together the flour, baking soda, and salt.

3. In a large bowl, cream together the butter, white sugar, and brown sugar until light and fluffy.

4. Beat in the vanilla extract.

5. Add the eggs one at a time, beating well after each addition.

6. Gradually mix in the dry ingredients until just combined.

7. Fold in the chocolate chips.

8. Drop the dough by tablespoonfuls onto the prepared baking sheet, spacing them about 2 inches apart.

9. Bake for 12-15 minutes, or until the edges are lightly golden.

10. Remove from the oven and let cool on the baking sheet for 5 minutes before transferring to a wire rack to cool completely.

Enjoy your delicious chewy chocolate chip cookies!
output_2:
Making chewy chocolate chip cookies is a delightful and simple process. Here's how you can make them at home:

Ingredients:
- 1 1/2 cups all-purpose flour
- 1/2 cup granulated sugar
- 1 teaspoon baking soda 
- 1 teaspoon salt
- 1/2 cup unsalted butter, at room temperature
- 1/2 cup brown sugar
- 2 large eggs
- 1 teaspoon vanilla extract
- 1/2 cup semisweet chocolate chips

Instructions:
1. Preheat the oven to 375°F (190°C).
2. In a bowl, mix together the flour, sugar, baking soda, and salt.
3. In another bowl, cream together the butter and brown sugar until light and fluffy.
4. Beat in the eggs, one at a time, making sure each one is fully incorporated before adding the next.
5. Add the vanilla extract and mix well.
6. Gradually mix in the dry ingredients, being careful not to overmix.
7. Stir in the chocolate chips.
8. Drop the dough by rounded tablespoons onto a prepared baking sheet, spacing them about 2 inches apart.
9. Bake for 12-15 minutes, or until the edges are lightly golden.
10. Allow the cookies to cool on the baking sheet for 5 minutes before transferring them to a wire rack to cool completely.

Enjoy your chewy and delicious chocolate chip cookies!

instruction: Suggest a recipe for a vegan dessert.
output_1:
One delicious vegan dessert recipe is for a Chocolate Avocado Mousse. Here's what you'll need:

Ingredients:
- 1 ripe avocado
- 1/2 cup of cocoa powder
- 1/2 cup of almond milk
- 1/2 cup of maple syrup
- 1/2 teaspoon of vanilla extract
- 1/2 cup of fresh berries (such as strawberries, blueberries, or raspberries)

Instructions:
1. Begin by mashing the avocado in a bowl until it's smooth and creamy.
2. Add the cocoa powder, almond milk, maple syrup, and vanilla extract to the mashed avocado and mix well.
3. Chill the mixture in the refrigerator for at least 30 minutes to allow the flavors to meld.
4. Just before serving, gently fold in the fresh berries.
5. Serve the chocolate avocado mousse in small bowls or ramekins and enjoy!

This dessert is not only vegan but also gluten-free, dairy-free, and low in calories. The combination of chocolate and avocado creates a rich and creamy texture that's both indulgent and healthy. The fresh berries add a sweet and tangy contrast to the mousse, making it a perfect dessert for any occasion.

- 1/4 cup maple syrup
- 1/4 cup silken tofu
- 1 teaspoon vanilla extract
- 1/2 cup shredded coconut
- Fresh berries or raspberry sauce for serving (optional)

Instructions:

1. In a food processor, blend the avocado until smooth.
2. Add the cocoa powder, coconut milk, maple syrup, tofu, vanilla extract and blend until smooth.
3. Chill the mousse in the refrigerator for at least 30 minutes.
4. Scoop the mousse into bowls or dessert cups.

instruction:
Describe the content of the article in a brief manner.

A study published earlier this year by Zee and her team examined the role of light in sleep for healthy adults in their 20s. Sleeping for only one night with a dim light, such as a TV set with the sound off, raised the blood sugar and heart rate of the young people during the sleep lab experiment. An elevated heart rate at night has been shown in prior studies to be a risk factor for future heart disease and early death, while higher blood sugar levels are a sign of insulin resistance, which can ultimately lead to type 2 diabetes.
output_1: The article discusses a study conducted by Zee and her team that examined the impact of light on sleep for healthy adults in their 20s. The study found that sleeping with a dim light, such as a TV set with the sound off, raised the blood sugar and heart rate of the young participants during the sleep lab experiment. This elevated heart rate at night is a risk factor for future heart disease and early death, while higher blood sugar levels are a sign of insulin resistance, which can lead to type 2 diabetes.
output_2: The article discusses a recent study by Zee and her team that investigated the impact of light on sleep for healthy adults in their 20s. The study found that exposure to dim light, such as a TV with the sound off, while sleeping for one night raised the blood sugar and heart rate of the young adults. Elevated heart rate at night is a risk factor for future heart disease and early death, while higher blood sugar levels indicate insulin resistance, which can lead to type 2 diabetes.

instruction:
Describe the responsibilities of the given job.

Security Officer
output_1:
The responsibilities of a Security Officer typically include the following:

1. Ensuring the safety and security of people and property: This involves patrolling designated areas, monitoring surveillance cameras, and responding to any security breaches or emergencies.

2. Enforcing rules and regulations: Security officers are responsible for enforcing rules and regulations set by the organization or property owner, such as access control, parking regulations, and no-smoking policies.

3. Providing customer service: Security officers often interact with the public, so they must be able to provide a high level of customer service, including answering questions, providing directions, and assisting with any issues or concerns.

4. Monitoring and reporting suspicious activity: Security officers are responsible for monitoring the environment for any suspicious or unusual activity, and reporting any incidents to the appropriate authorities.

5. Maintaining security equipment: Security officers must be familiar with and maintain all security equipment, such as access control systems, surveillance cameras, and alarm systems.

6. Conducting security checks: Security officers may be responsible for conducting security checks, such as bag searches or ID verification, at designated areas or events.

7. Providing escort services: Security officers may be required to provide escort services for individuals or groups, such as visitors or employees, to ensure their safety and security.

Overall, the responsibilities of a Security Officer involve ensuring the safety and security of people and property, enforcing rules and regulations, providing customer service, monitoring and reporting suspicious activity, maintaining security equipment, conducting security checks, and providing escort services.
output_2: Security Officer is responsible for the protection and security of people, property, and assets. Their duties include patrolling designated areas, monitoring security systems, enforcing rules and regulations, and responding to emergencies. They may also conduct security assessments, investigate suspicious activities, and report incidents to the appropriate authorities. Additionally, they are responsible for maintaining good relationships with the public, providing information and assistance, and ensuring that all security protocols are followed.

instruction:
Provide a list of the skills that may help you find the job.

Crew Members
output_1:
Here is a list of skills that may help you find a job as a crew member:

1. Customer service skills: The ability to provide excellent customer service is essential for crew members as they are often the first point of contact for customers.

2. Communication skills: Good communication skills are important for crew members as they need to be able to communicate effectively with customers, colleagues, and management.

3. Teamwork: Crew members often work in teams, so the ability to work well with others is crucial.

4. Time management: Crew members need to be able to manage their time effectively to ensure that tasks are completed on time and to a high standard.

5. Attention to detail: Crew members need to be able to pay attention to detail to ensure that tasks are completed accurately and to a high standard.

6. Flexibility: Crew members may be required to work different shifts and be flexible with their availability.

7. Physical fitness: Crew members may be required to stand for long periods, lift heavy objects, and move quickly, so physical fitness is important.

8. Basic computer skills: Crew members may be required to use computer systems to complete tasks such as taking orders or tracking inventory.

9. Restaurant or retail experience: Experience in the restaurant or retail industry can be beneficial for crew members as it provides a good understanding of the industry and the expectations of customers.

10. Positive attitude: A positive attitude and a willingness to learn are important for crew members as they are often the face of the company and need to be able to handle difficult situations with a smile.
output_2:
1. Customer service skills
2. Attention to detail
3. Teamwork
4. Time management
5. Multitasking
6. Communication skills
7. Flexibility
8. Adaptability
9. Physical stamina
10. Able to lift and carry heavy objects
11. Ability to follow instructions and training
12. Responsibility and accountability
13. Basic food handling and safety knowledge
14. Cash handling and sales experience.

instruction:
Give a brief explanation of the requested part of the paper.

Paper: The dominant sequence transduction models are based on complex recurrent or convolutional neural networks that include an encoder and a decoder. The best performing models also connect the encoder and decoder through an attention mechanism. We propose a new simple network architecture, the Transformer, based solely on attention mechanisms, dispensing with recurrence and convolutions entirely. Experiments on two machine translation tasks show these models to be superior in quality while being more parallelizable and requiring significantly less time to train. Our model achieves 28.4 BLEU on the WMT 2014 English-to-German translation task, improving over the existing best results, including ensembles, by over 2 BLEU. On the WMT 2014 English-to-French translation task, our model establishes a new single-model state-of-the-art BLEU score of 41.8 after training for 3.5 days on eight GPUs, a small fraction of the training costs of the best models from the literature. We show that the Transformer generalizes well to other tasks by applying it successfully to English constituency parsing both with large and limited training data.
Explain: The dominant sequence transduction models
output_1: The paper discusses the current state-of-the-art sequence transduction models, which are based on complex recurrent or convolutional neural networks that include an encoder and a decoder. These models also use an attention mechanism to connect the encoder and decoder. The authors propose a new simple network architecture called the Transformer, which is based solely on attention mechanisms and does not use recurrence or convolutions. The paper evaluates the performance of the Transformer on two machine translation tasks and compares it to existing models. The results show that the Transformer outperforms existing models in quality while being more parallelizable and requiring less time to train. The paper also demonstrates the generalization of the Transformer to other tasks such as English constituency parsing.
output_2: The paper discusses the prevalent models used for sequence transduction tasks, such as machine translation, which involve translating one sequence of words into another. These models rely on complex recurrent neural networks or convolutional neural networks, with the inclusion of an encoder and decoder. The best-performing models also incorporate attention mechanisms to facilitate the flow of information between the encoder and decoder. The proposed Transformer model, on the other hand, relies solely on attention mechanisms and does not utilize any recurrence or convolutions.

instruction: Recommend some helpful activities or conversation starters to use at meetups to break the ice.
output_1:
Here are some activities or conversation starters that can help break the ice at a meetup:

1. Icebreaker games: There are many icebreaker games that can be played at a meetup, such as Two Truths and a Lie, Would You Rather, or Herding Cats. These games are a fun way to get to know people and can be adapted to fit the group's interests.
2. Group challenges: Another way to break the ice is to have a group challenge, such as a scavenger hunt or a team-building exercise. This can be a fun way to get people to work together and get to know each other.
3. Group discussions: A group discussion can be a great way to get people talking and sharing their thoughts and ideas. You could start with a general topic and then allow the conversation to flow naturally, or you could provide a list of discussion topics to choose from.
4. Speed networking: Speed networking is a structured way to meet a large number of people in a short amount of time. You could set up a series of one-on-one or small group conversations, or you could have a more informal "speed dating" style event.
5. Group activities: You could also plan group activities, such as a potluck dinner, a group outing to a local attraction, or a volunteer project. These activities can be a fun way to bond with others and get to know them in a more relaxed setting.

Remember, the key to breaking the ice at a meetup is to create a welcoming and inclusive environment where people feel comfortable sharing their thoughts and ideas.
output_2:
Here are some activities or conversation starters that can help break the ice at a meetup:

1. Icebreaker questions: Prepare a list of icebreaker questions that can help people get to know each other better. Examples include "What's your favorite hobby?", "What's the best vacation you've ever been on?", "What's your favorite book or movie?", etc.

2. Group games: Play a group game that requires interaction and communication. Examples include "Two Truths and a Lie", "Would You Rather", or "Charades".

3. Introduce yourself: Ask each person to introduce themselves and share one interesting fact about themselves.

4. Speed Networking: Set up a speed networking session where everyone gets a chance to talk to each other for a few minutes.

5. Group challenges: Divide the group into teams and have them work together to solve a challenge or problem.

6. Pair up: Assign each person a partner and have them spend a few minutes discussing a specific topic or question.

7. Show and tell: Ask each person to bring something that represents them and share a little bit about it.

8. Group discussion: Start a group discussion on a common interest or topic to encourage conversation and collaboration.

Remember, the key is to keep it light and fun to create a relaxed atmosphere where people can feel comfortable and engaged.

instruction:
Extract the method that has been used in the research from the abstract of the paper. Give the exact sentences from the abstract that discuss the method.

We present a state-of-the-art speech recognition system developed using end-to-end deep learning. Our architecture is significantly simpler than traditional speech systems, which rely on laboriously engineered processing pipelines; these traditional systems also tend to perform poorly when used in noisy environments. In contrast, our system does not need hand-designed components to model background noise, reverberation, or speaker variation, but instead directly learns a function that is robust to such effects. We do not need a phoneme dictionary, nor even the concept of a "phoneme." Key to our approach is a well-optimized RNN training system that uses multiple GPUs, as well as a set of novel data synthesis techniques that allow us to efficiently obtain a large amount of varied data for training. Our system, called Deep Speech, outperforms previously published results on the widely studied Switchboard Hub5'00, achieving 16.0% error on the full test set. Deep Speech also handles challenging noisy environments better than widely used, state-of-the-art commercial speech systems.Collapse
output_1: The method used in the research is end-to-end deep learning. The abstract states that "We present a state-of-the-art speech recognition system developed using end-to-end deep learning."
output_2: The method used in the research is end-to-end deep learning.

instruction:
Create a short, concise summary of the paper based on its abstract.

Few-shot learning (FSL) is one of the key future steps in machine learning and raises a lot of attention. In this paper, we focus on the FSL problem of dialogue understanding, which contains two closely related tasks: intent detection and slot filling. Dialogue understanding has been proven to benefit a lot from jointly learning the two sub-tasks. However, such joint learning becomes challenging in the few-shot scenarios: on the one hand, the sparsity of samples greatly magnifies the difficulty of modeling the connection between the two tasks; on the other hand, how to jointly learn multiple tasks in the few-shot setting is still less investigated. In response to this, we introduce FewJoint, the first FSL benchmark for joint dialogue understanding. FewJoint provides a new corpus with 59 different dialogue domains from real industrial API and a code platform to ease FSL experiment set-up, which are expected to advance the research of this field. Further, we find that insufficient performance of the few-shot setting often leads to noisy sharing between two sub-task and disturbs joint learning. To tackle this, we guide slot with explicit intent information and propose a novel trust gating mechanism that blocks low-confidence intent information to ensure high quality sharing. Besides, we introduce a Reptile-based meta-learning strategy to achieve better generalization in unseen few-shot domains. In the experiments, the proposed method brings significant improvements on two datasets and achieve new state-of-the-art performance.
output_1: The paper introduces FewJoint, a benchmark for few-shot learning in dialogue understanding, and proposes a method to improve joint learning in this setting. The method includes using explicit intent information to guide slot filling and a trust gating mechanism to ensure high-quality sharing, as well as a Reptile-based meta-learning strategy for better generalization. The proposed method achieves significant improvements on two datasets and sets a new state-of-the-art performance.
output_2: The paper introduces a new few-shot learning benchmark for dialogue understanding, which involves intent detection and slot filling. The joint learning of these tasks becomes difficult in the few-shot setting due to the sparsity of samples and the need to jointly learn multiple tasks. The paper proposes a method that uses explicit intent information to guide slot filling and a trust gating mechanism to ensure high-quality sharing between the two tasks. Additionally, the paper uses a Reptile-based meta-learning strategy to improve generalization in unseen few-shot domains.

instruction:
Someone gives you some information about where they want to go and what they enjoy seeing and doing. Describe a proper road trip for them and find the best stops and sctivities in the way.

I'm looking for a west coast road trip. My goal is to start near San Diego and travel to Los Angeles.
output_1:
Great! A west coast road trip from San Diego to Los Angeles is a fantastic adventure. Here's a suggested itinerary with some of the best stops and activities along the way:

Day 1: San Diego to Santa Barbara

* Start your day early and head north on Interstate 5.
* Stop at the historic Mission San Luis Obispo de Tolosa, a beautiful Spanish mission founded in 1772.
* Continue driving to Santa Barbara, known for its stunning coastline, beaches, and Spanish architecture.
* Spend the night in Santa Barbara and explore the city's vibrant downtown area.

Day 2: Santa Barbara to Los Angeles

* Start your day with a visit to the Santa Barbara Mission, a beautiful example of Spanish colonial architecture.
* Drive along the Pacific Coast Highway (Route 1) to the charming town of Cambria.
* Take a scenic drive through Big Sur, a rugged and breathtaking coastal region with stunning views of the Pacific Ocean.
* Continue driving to Los Angeles, where you can explore the city's many attractions, including the Hollywood Walk of Fame, the Griffith Observatory, and the Los Angeles County Museum of Art.

Some additional stops and activities you might enjoy along the way:

* In Santa Barbara, visit the Santa Barbara Zoo or take a whale-watching tour.
* In Big Sur, hike the Ventana Wilderness Trail or visit the Big Sur Bakery & Restaurant.
* In Los Angeles, visit Universal Studios Hollywood or take a tour of the historic Hollywood Forever Cemetery.

I hope this itinerary helps you plan a memorable west coast road trip from San Diego to Los Angeles!
output_2:
Starting from San Diego, your west coast road trip will take you to the beautiful city of Los Angeles. Here's a suggested itinerary for your journey, with stops and activities along the way:

Day 1: San Diego to Santa Barbara

* Drive north on I-5 and enjoy the picturesque coastal views.
* Stop in Solvang, a quaint Danish town with charming shops and bakeries. Visit the Solvang Vintage Motorcycle Museum for a glimpse into the region's automotive history.
* Continue to Santa Barbara, known for its stunning beaches, Spanish architecture, and wine country. Visit the Santa Barbara Mission and explore the beautiful Santa Barbara Botanic Garden.

Day 2: Santa Barbara to Big Sur

* Drive north on Highway 1, a scenic route that hugs the rugged California coastline.
* Stop at McWay Falls, a breathtaking waterfall that cascades onto a beach, accessible through a short trail.
* Continue to Big Sur, a picturesque region of redwood forests, rugged cliffs, and pristine beaches. Hike the Ventana Wilderness Trail or visit the Big Sur Bakery and Restaurant for a delicious meal.

Day 3: Big Sur to Los Angeles

* Drive east on Highway 101 to Paso Robles, a wine country region with over 20 wineries. Visit the Hearst Castle, a lavish estate built by newspaper publisher William Randolph Hearst.
* Continue to Los Angeles, passing through the beautiful Santa Ynez Valley and Malibu.

Los Angeles is a vibrant city with many attractions, including the world-famous Hollywood, the Griffith Observatory, and the Getty Center. Spend the last day of your trip exploring the city's culture, food, and entertainment.

This road trip offers a mix of natural beauty, cultural experiences, and local flavors. Enjoy your journey!

instruction: Create a template in markdown to create scope for Jira tickets. Members should use this template as a checklist to ensure they have included all the necessary information when creating a ticket.
output_1:
# Jira Ticket Scope Template

## Description

### Problem Statement

* Briefly describe the problem or issue that needs to be addressed.

### Impact

* Explain the impact of the problem on the project or team.

### Urgency

* Determine the urgency of the issue and prioritize accordingly.

## Requirements

### Functional Requirements

* List the functional requirements that need to be met to resolve the issue.

### Non-Functional Requirements

* List the non-functional requirements that need to be met to resolve the issue.

### Acceptance Criteria

* Define the acceptance criteria that need to be met to consider the issue resolved.

### User Stories

* List any user stories that are affected by the issue.

### Use Cases

* List any use cases that are affected by the issue.

### Test Cases

* List any test cases that need to be executed to verify the resolution of the issue.

### Dependencies

* List any dependencies that need to be resolved before the issue can be addressed.

### Risks

* List any risks associated with addressing the issue.

### Assumptions

* List any assumptions that need to be made to address the issue.

### Constraints

* List any constraints that need to be considered when addressing the issue.

### Known Issues

* List any known issues that are related to the issue being addressed.

### Next Steps

* Outline the next steps that need to be taken to address the issue.

### Estimated Time

* Estimate the time required to address the issue.

### Estimated Resources

* Estimate the resources required to address the issue.

### Responsible Team Member

* Identify the team member responsible for addressing the issue.

### Due Date

* Identify the due date for resolving the issue.

### Status

* Update the status of the issue as it progresses through the resolution process.

instruction:
Write a Jira ticket for the given task.

New Employee onboarding
output_1:
Title: Improve New Employee Onboarding Process

Description:

The current onboarding process for new employees is time-consuming and inefficient. It involves multiple steps and departments, and new employees often feel overwhelmed and disconnected from the company. The goal of this project is to streamline the onboarding process and make it more effective and engaging for new employees.

Steps:

1. Conduct a review of the current onboarding process and identify areas for improvement.
2. Develop a new onboarding process that is streamlined and efficient.
3. Train all relevant departments and employees on the new process.
4. Implement the new onboarding process and monitor its effectiveness.
5. Continuously evaluate and improve the onboarding process as needed.

Priority: High

Assignee: HR Department

Due Date: 30 days from the start of the project.
output_2:
Title: New Employee Onboarding

Description:

The aim of this task is to create and implement a comprehensive onboarding program for new employees joining our company. The program should include the following steps:

1. Pre-onboarding:
- A welcome email to the new employee from the HR team, introducing the company culture and values.
- A detailed onboarding checklist that outlines all the tasks to be completed by the new employee, including IT setup, office location and access, and company policies.
- A company handbook or an online portal containing all the necessary information about the company, including its history, mission, and values.
- Setting up a meeting with the new employee’s manager to discuss the employee's role, responsibilities, and expectations.

2. Onboarding:
- An orientation program to introduce the new employee to the company, its culture, and values.
- An introduction to the team and the company’s organizational structure.
- An overview of the company’s products or services and their role in the team.
- A tour of the office and introductions to key personnel.
- An opportunity to ask questions and receive feedback on the onboarding process.

3. Post-onboarding:
- A follow-up meeting with the employee’s manager to ensure they are comfortable and settled in their role.
- Regular check-ins to ensure the employee is meeting their targets and achieving their goals.

This Jira ticket will help to ensure that our onboarding process is efficient and effective, and that new employees are set up for success in their new roles.
